# Doc Moves: Redirects and Link Updates

When you **move**, **rename**, or **consolidate** a doc (or merge several docs into one), do both of the following so old URLs work and the link checker stays green.

## 1. Add redirect_from on the destination

In the **destination** file's YAML frontmatter, add (or append to) `redirect_from` with the previous path(s) under `/docs/` so the old URL continues to work.

For **custom `slug`** (URL different from the default path), see **[Doc slugs and redirect_from](mdc:doc-slugs-and-redirects.mdc)** — you must still list every superseded URL under `redirect_from`.

- **Path format:** Use the path as it would appear in the URL (this project's plugin expects paths from site root, e.g. with leading slash).
  - Example: old file `docs/infra-as-code-management/get-started/onboarding-guide.md` → add `/docs/infra-as-code-management/get-started/onboarding-guide`
- **Multiple old paths:** If the file had several previous locations or aliases, add each as a list item under `redirect_from`.

**Example frontmatter after move:**
```yaml
---
title: Get started with IaCM
description: A self-service onboarding guide for Harness IaCM.
sidebar_position: 20
redirect_from:
  - /docs/infra-as-code-management/get-started/onboarding-guide
---
```

**Optional:** For important or cross-section moves, also add the same redirect in `_server-redirects` (Netlify format: `old_path new_path`).

**`3k-docs/` pages that have been rewritten with real content (not import wrappers) do not get this for free.** `redirect_from` is only honored for files under `docs/` today — `docusaurus.config.ts`'s `scanDocsForPathsAndRedirects()` walks `docsDir` (`docs/`) only and hardcodes the `/docs/...` path prefix, so `redirect_from` set on a `3k-docs/` page is currently inert (no build failure, just a silent 404 on the old URL). If you are moving files inside a rewritten module (e.g. the Continuous Delivery restructuring), use `_server-redirects` for now and flag the `scanDocsForPathsAndRedirects()` gap to whoever owns `docusaurus.config.ts` rather than relying on frontmatter `redirect_from`.

## 2. Update all in-repo links to the new path

Update every link that pointed to the old path(s) so it points to the new path. Otherwise the link checker can report broken links even when `redirect_from` exists.

1. **Identify old paths:** List every URL path that no longer exists (e.g. `/docs/.../old-slug`). Include paths from consolidated or deleted files.
2. **Search the repo:** Search for links using those paths — in `docs/`, `release-notes/`, `sidebars.ts`, and any other content (e.g. `href="..."`, `](/docs/...`, `](/release-notes/...`).
3. **Update each link:** Change the link to the **new path**. If the content lives on a different page or tab (e.g. DynamicMarkdownSelector overview), point to that page and use a hash if needed (e.g. `.../module-registry-overview#registeredmodulesettings--top-level-overview`).

**What to search for:** Markdown links `](/docs/.../old-path)`, HTML/JSX `href="/docs/.../old-path"`, sidebars doc IDs or paths. Use the old path in multiple forms (with/without leading slash, with `.md` for relative links).

**Example:** After consolidating four docs into `module-registry-overview.md`, search for all four old slugs, update each hit to `/docs/.../module-registry-overview` (plus hash when linking to a specific section), and ensure the destination has `redirect_from` for all four old paths.

## 3. Update sidebar configuration when crossing system boundaries

When moving files between module root and subfolders, the sidebar system changes:

- **Moving FROM module root TO subfolder** (e.g., `/docs/platform/file.md` → `/docs/platform/subfolder/file.md`):
  - Remove the explicit doc ID entry from `sidebars.ts`
  - Add `sidebar_position: [number]` to the file's frontmatter (it will auto-generate via `_category_.json` or `{ type: 'autogenerated', dirName: '...' }`)

- **Moving FROM subfolder TO module root** (e.g., `/docs/platform/subfolder/file.md` → `/docs/platform/file.md`):
  - Add the doc ID explicitly to the appropriate items array in `sidebars.ts`
  - Keep `sidebar_position` in frontmatter (determines order within the manual array)

Go to **Sidebar Navigation Configuration** in `CLAUDE.md` for details.

## 4. Sync 3k-docs content-reuse imports

If a `3k-docs/` wrapper page imports the file you just moved (`import X from '@site/docs/<old-path>'`), update that import to the new path in the same PR. See **[3k-docs content reuse](mdc:3k-docs.mdc)** for how to find importers and how to handle moves that aren't a clean 1:1 rename. Skipping this is what caused the HDH-561 build breakage — the failure only surfaces at `docusaurus build` time, after merge, not in this PR's diff.

## 5. Sync sidebars-3k-docs.ts when moving files inside 3k-docs/

If you move, rename, or delete a file or folder under `3k-docs/` itself (not just `docs/`), also check `sidebars-3k-docs.ts` for `id:` and `dirName:` references to the old path, and update them in the same PR. See **[3k-docs content reuse](mdc:3k-docs.mdc)** for the exact grep commands and the manual-vs-autogenerated distinction (mirrors the `sidebars.ts` duality in `CLAUDE.md`). `dirName:` folder renames are never auto-fixed by CI, so these need a human every time.

## When to apply

- You move or rename a doc under `docs/` or `release-notes/`.
- You consolidate several docs into one (e.g. an overview with DynamicMarkdownSelector).
- You delete a doc that was linked from elsewhere.
- The user reports broken links after a refactor.
